\emph on
Lyapunov exponents in this setting have been studied directly at the single-protein / small-peptide scale.
 * Braxenthaler,
 Unger,
 Auerbach,
 Given & Moult,
 "Chaos in protein dynamics," Proteins 29:417–425 (1997) —
 perturbed a protein fragment in explicit solvent by 10⁻³–10⁻⁹ Å and found trajectories diverged to ~1 Å RMSD within 1–2 ps regardless of starting conformation,
 and perturbing more than 1–2 ps before a conformational transition erased that transition in the perturbed trajectory.
 * Zhou & Wang,
 "Chaos in Biomolecular Dynamics," J.
 Phys.
 Chem.
 100:8101 (1996) —
 for an α-helix,
 Lyapunov exponents came out around 0.001–0.01 ps⁻¹.
 * A later myoglobin simulation put the maximum Lyapunov exponent around 10 ps⁻¹ —
 much faster divergence,
 showing the exponent is very sensitive to system size/force field/method.
 * An undergrad-style redo on ubiquitin (NAMD/VMD) reported exponential divergence with λ ≈ 10.5 ps⁻¹,
 i.e.
 loss of predictability in well under a picosecond.
