\emph on
Predictability timescale vs.
 biological timescale.
 The striking thing in the biology is the separation of timescales:
 chaotic divergence at the atomic level happens on ~0.1–10 ps,
 while functionally relevant conformational changes (domain motions,
 allostery,
 folding) happen on ns–ms.
 So the microscopic trajectory is essentially unpredictable almost immediately,
 yet coarse,
 collective observables (RMSD to a folded state,
 reaction coordinates,
 free energy along a pathway) remain statistically reproducible —
 this is the same kind of scale separation that makes hydrodynamics work despite molecular chaos underneath it.
 This is really the crux of why "amplification of small disturbances" doesn't obviously translate into unpredictable biology.
