\emph on
The Nosé–Hoover thermostat adds one (or a chain of) fictitious extra degree(s) of freedom coupled to the physical system such that the extended system is still genuinely Hamiltonian (deterministic,
 time–reversible,
 and —
 after a time rescaling —
 volume–preserving in an extended,
 non–standard measure),
 while the marginal distribution of the physical subsystem,
 averaged over long trajectories (assuming ergodicity),
 is exactly canonical.
 This is the cleanest bridge between "symplectic dynamics" and "canonical ensemble" you'll find,
 because it keeps you inside Hamiltonian mechanics rather than jumping to a stochastic Langevin picture.
