\emph on
The Aerts group has run actual Bell–type (CHSH) experiments on human judgments about concept combinations —
 things like judging "The Animal Acts" and "The Animal Eats the Food" —
 and found genuine,
 statistically significant CHSH violations,
 which by Pitowsky's theorem rules out any classical joint–probability (Kolmogorovian) model of the two judgments.
 They model this with entangled states in complex Hilbert space,
 and in that formal sense,
 yes:
 conditioning on ("collapsing") one component's outcome changes the conditional statistics of the other in a way no classical local hidden–variable story can reproduce —
 structurally the same signature as physical entanglement.
\emph default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Well,
 hot damn.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\emph on
But here's the wrinkle you should know about:
 their measured violations sometimes exceed Tsirelson's bound (~2√2),
 the ceiling that ordinary quantum entanglement itself can't cross.
 That's a big deal,
 because it means the correlations aren't merely "quantum–like" —
 they're stronger than anything a real quantum system,
 or a real tensor–product Hilbert–space model with the usual assumptions,
 can produce.
 So the honest answer is:
 the analogy holds at the level of "non–classical,
 context–dependent,
 Bell–violating correlational structure," but it does not obviously hold at the level of the precise mathematical constraints (Tsirelson bound,
 and by extension things like monogamy–of–entanglement inequalities) that make physical entanglement physical.
\emph default

